  "body": "**Describe the bug**\r\nCurrently, nethermind responds to an invalid jwt token on the auth port with a 200 response code which makes it a bit ugly to parse response as an auth error. Here's a sample response for an `eth_syncing` request with an invalid jwt signature\r\n\r\n```\r\n*   Trying 127.0.0.1:8551...\r\n* TCP_NODELAY set\r\n* Connected to localhost (127.0.0.1) port 8551 (#0)\r\n> POST / HTTP/1.1\r\n> Host: localhost:8551\r\n> User-Agent: curl/7.68.0\r\n> Accept: */*\r\n> Content-Type: application/json\r\n> Authorization: Bearer eyJ0eXAiOiJKV1QiLCJhbGciOiJIUzI1NiJ9.eyJpYXQiOjE2NjE5NzIxMzZ9.3jtdUJRjEX-3RnOrjjTlA7Gl-ho9ZDEkDPMj99Gwq\r\nO0\r\n> Content-Length: 104\r\n> \r\n* upload completely sent off: 104 out of 104 bytes\r\n* Mark bundle as not supporting multiuse\r\n< HTTP/1.1 200 OK\r\n< Content-Type: application/json\r\n< Date: Wed, 31 Aug 2022 18:55:36 GMT\r\n< Server: Kestrel\r\n< Transfer-Encoding: chunked\r\n< \r\n* Connection #0 to host localhost left intact\r\n{\"jsonrpc\":\"2.0\",\"error\":{\"code\":-32700,\"message\":\"Authentication error\"},\"id\":null}\r\n\r\n```\r\nIt would be helpful and cleaner if nethermind returns a 403 response code for invalid jwt errors.\r\n\r\n\r\n**To Reproduce**\r\n\r\nSend a json-rpc request on the auth port with an invalid jwt.\r\n\r\n**Expected behavior**\r\nShould return 403 http status code.\r\n\r\n**Desktop (please complete the following information):**\r\n - OS: Ubuntu 20.04\r\n - Browser Brave\r\n - Version latest\r\n\r\n",
